  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Restoring access to Education-in-Emergencies (EiE) for conflict-affected school age children in East Darfur state Sudan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">An estimated four million school-aged children between 4-16 years of age live in seven conflict-affected states in Sudan, which have the highest rate of out-of-school children in the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region (UNICEF, 2015). According to the 2017 Humanitarian Needs Overview (HNO), about 1.7 million conflict affected children (948,141 IDP, 229,129 refugees and 85,785 returnees) are in need of Education in Emergencies (EiE) support. Furthermore, it is noted that the total numbers of conflict-affected children in need of EiE Sudan have been increasing due to not only internal conflicts in the seven states but also the unstable political situation and recent famine in South Sudan. According to the 15 November UNHCR Sudan South Sudanese Refugee (SSR) emergency population update, there are 805,169 new SSRs in Sudan since December 2013; 116,847 SSRs in East Darfur state, of whom around 46,739 are children aged 3-13, settled in 13 locations amongst host communities in urban and rural settlements and in the two camps of Kario and El Nimir. It is estimated that 60% of the refugees in East Darfur are living out of camps in 11 settlements across 9 localities. Unlike the refugees in Kario and El Nimir, those living in settlements and amongst host communities, are living in harsh conditions, with limited access to basic social services and protection services. The action will target all the 15,000 (2,510 SSRs and 12,490 host community per-school and school aged children) in areas around the 9 schools in El Ferdous locality with access to education and Child protection activities. This will include, for all targeted schools: supplies, enrollment campaign as well as the capacity building for service provider , as well as establish learning spaces to reach the 11,456 out of school and pre-school children (8,946 from the host community and 2,510 from the SSR).</narrative>
  </description>
